What’s even sadder is that I’ve never had more than a paltry $300/month budget while living in The Bahamas (and I made sure to drop items from the budget like heat and electricity—I tried experiementing with a $250/month budget, but it was *v-e-r-y* tight).

While we were in The Bahamas, one evening we saw a couple that was walking down the road. It was almost midnight and they were both wearing all black. A little concerning. (As are Paris Hilton’s safety tips on The Today Show)

Back to the budget.

Nice-to-Haves: In Canada, how do we expect people to know that $7/month won’t come even close to paying the bills? It’s like asking other people (i.e. taxpayers) to pay for our non-necessity family dinners at Timmy Ho’s or home phone bills that change to sky-high once you leave the bah.

Despite the accusations that I’m “bashing” The Bahamas right now, my reason for this section is NOT to bash—-rather it’s to offer the following specifications of a No-Spend Countdown on Canadian soil:

Ages of the children: 15, 14, 2 
 Location of the family: Winnipeg Beach (NBerg Beach) 
 School-year budget for a family of 5: $?
